# FreshLens — Architecture Rules

## 1. Multi-tenancy via Postgres RLS

Every business table: `tenant_id` column + RLS policy in the **same migration**.

```sql
-- Policy pattern
USING (tenant_id = current_setting('app.tenant_id')::uuid)
```

- API middleware sets `app.tenant_id` from auth JWT at request start
- App-code tenant filters are defense-in-depth only — never the sole safeguard
- Core tables: `tenants` → `users`, `products`, `scans`, `batches`, `alerts`

## 2. Async inference only

```
POST /scan → upload image (R2) → enqueue Celery job → return 202 immediately
Worker → FL-2TC (Tier 1 identify, Tier 2 freshness) → write result to DB
```

- **Never** run CNN inside a FastAPI request handler
- Redis keys: `tenant:{tenant_id}:...` (queue, cache, results)
- Version 1: one product per photo; quantity is vendor-confirmed at scan time

## 3. Record shapes

`scans`: `image_path`, `freshness_score`, `classification`, `model_version`, `tenant_id`, linked `batch_id` (optional)

`batches`: `tenant_id`, `product_id`, `intake_date`, `quantity_received`, `quantity_remaining`, `shelf_life_days` (admin-configured per category; used for V1 static aging alerts)

## 4. Out of scope — do not build unless explicitly requested

IoT/smart scales · automated procurement/supply-chain · accounting/tax modules

## 5. Before merging DB or API scan changes, verify

- [ ] Migration includes RLS for every new tenant-scoped table
- [ ] No inline model inference in route handlers
- [ ] Redis keys are tenant-namespaced
- [ ] `.env.example` updated if new env vars added
